[~f.erfurth] Your Android SDK path in the Titanium CLI differs from the one in Titanium Studio. The CLI is pointing to the correct location:

{code}
/home/f.erfurth/Development/android-sdks
{code}

However, Studio is pointing to:

{code}
/home/f.erfurth/Development/android-sdk-home
{code}

Which may exist, but needs to be the same as the Titanium CLI. Please update the Android SDK path in Studio to point to the same one as the Titanium CLI:

{code}
/home/f.erfurth/Development/android-sdks
{code}

[~f.erfurth] Hmm, sorry I closed it. Reopened it until we solve this. :)

So, what we need to do is first verify that the Titanium CLI can see the Android SDK and the targets. You can do this by running:

{code}
ti info -t android
{code}

I saw in the attached {{titanium-info_current.txt}} that the CLI indeed did find the Android SDKs.

To test that the Titanium CLI can build apps just fine, go to any Titanium app, then run the following:

{code}
ti build -p android --build-only
{code}

If the app builds fine, then we can safely say the issue is in Titanium Studio, not the Titanium CLI build system.

The next thing to do is to set the Android SDK path in Studio to the correct location. You just need the Android SDK. You do not need the Android NDK for building apps. If Studio is complaining still, then we need to further investigate.

Sorry to make you run around, but I want to make sure you can get up and running. :)

[~f.erfurth] Great! Glad you solved the problem. :)

We do have a checklist, but it's only in the CLI, not in Studio. You simply run:

{code}
ti setup check
{code}

It's not comprehensive, but it does check the obvious stuff.
